<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="321" pageId="19" pageNumber="320" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1874,2009]" lastBlockId="20.[151,1437,150,825]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="321" pageId="19" pageNumber="320">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1874,1900]" pageId="19" pageNumber="320">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[329,416,1875,1901]" pageId="19" pageNumber="320">Female</emphasis>
: Can be recognized using the following combination of morphological traits: body size approximately 
<quantity box="[294,376,1911,1937]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="19" pageNumber="320" unit="mm" value="12.0">12 mm</quantity>
; integument dark brown, except mandibles, antennae including scape (
<figureCitation box="[1173,1257,1911,1937]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–44" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1732,1756]" captionTargetBox="[181,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-224@19.[180,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 41–44. Megachile rugipuncta. 41. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of female. 42. Front view of female. 43. Dorsal view of metasoma of female. 44. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494667/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="320">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
), legs including all coxa orange-red; head, scutellum and sometimes T1-T3 may also be orange red. Punctation diagnostic, as follows: on tergal discs, finely and densely punctate, interspaces at most one puncture diameter (
<figureCitation box="[1200,1285,1983,2009]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–44" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1732,1756]" captionTargetBox="[181,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-224@19.[180,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 41–44. Megachile rugipuncta. 41. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of female. 42. Front view of female. 43. Dorsal view of metasoma of female. 44. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494667/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="320">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
); on mesonotum, punctures similar to tergal punctures, punctation sparser, with interspaces shiny, up to 1.5 puncture diameters (
<figureCitation box="[160,243,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–44" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1732,1756]" captionTargetBox="[181,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-224@19.[180,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 41–44. Megachile rugipuncta. 41. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of female. 42. Front view of female. 43. Dorsal view of metasoma of female. 44. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494667/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
); on vertex, punctures particularly coarse, approximately twice as large as on mesonotum, with interspaces up to one puncture diameter wide (
<figureCitation box="[537,620,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–44" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1732,1756]" captionTargetBox="[181,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-224@19.[180,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 41–44. Megachile rugipuncta. 41. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of female. 42. Front view of female. 43. Dorsal view of metasoma of female. 44. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494667/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). T2 but not T3 laterally with fovea. Clypeus apically with wide, impunctate shiny margin (
<figureCitation box="[368,455,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–44" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1732,1756]" captionTargetBox="[181,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-224@19.[180,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 41–44. Megachile rugipuncta. 41. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of female. 42. Front view of female. 43. Dorsal view of metasoma of female. 44. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494667/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
). Vestiture predominantly white, scopa black on S6, vertex without appressed, brown vestiture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,150,825]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,331,357]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Male</emphasis>
(first description): Body length 
<quantity box="[623,705,331,357]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" unit="mm" value="12.0">12 mm</quantity>
; integument dark brown, at least legs and sternites partly orange. T2 but not T3 with fovea. T6 with preapical carina strongly denticulate, strongly produced apically. Front tarsi unmodified, integument brown-orange, tarsal segments 2, 3 and to some extent 4 ventrally with a loosely defined dark brown maculation. Punctation on tergites particularly fine and dense; punctures slightly larger on mesonotum, and much larger on vertex laterally (
<figureCitation box="[511,596,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–44" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1732,1756]" captionTargetBox="[181,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-224@19.[180,1407,786,1708]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 41–44. Megachile rugipuncta. 41. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of female. 42. Front view of female. 43. Dorsal view of metasoma of female. 44. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494667/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,150,825]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,459,510,536]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Geographic variation</emphasis>
: Some specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[744,806,511,537]" name="Israel" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Israel</collectingCountry>
(among which a female from Hazeva included in the molecular phylogeny with number PAMEG009-21; 
<figureCitation box="[751,818,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1687,1711]" captionTargetBox="[175,1411,523,1654]" captionTargetId="figure-175@3.[175,1412,522,1661]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Phylogenetic tree based on maximum likelihood analyses of the mitochondrial gene COI; numbers above the branches indicate statistical support based on 1000 bootstrap replicates (values below 50 are omitted)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494655" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494655/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), corresponding to the type specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[1312,1429,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tkalcui">
<emphasis box="[1312,1429,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">M. tkalcui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, placed here in synonymy with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Praz &amp; Al-Shahat &amp; Gadallah" authorityYear="2021" box="[503,665,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugipuncta">
<emphasis box="[503,665,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">M. rugipuncta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, have the integument of the head, scutellum and T1-T2 orange-red; 
<materialsCitation country="Israel" location="Israel" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" specimenCount="1">
<typeStatus box="[151,335,619,645]" isOtherTypeStatus="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">other specimens</typeStatus>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[408,470,619,645]" name="Israel" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Israel</collectingCountry>
(including the female from Hameshar, Shitim, included in the molecular phylogeny with number PAMEG010-21; 
<figureCitation box="[490,554,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1687,1711]" captionTargetBox="[175,1411,523,1654]" captionTargetId="figure-175@3.[175,1412,522,1661]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Phylogenetic tree based on maximum likelihood analyses of the mitochondrial gene COI; numbers above the branches indicate statistical support based on 1000 bootstrap replicates (values below 50 are omitted)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494655" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494655/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), as well as the
</materialsCitation>
<materialsCitation country="Jordan" location="In" municipality="For" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" specimenCount="1" specimenCount-female="1" typeStatus="lectotype">
<typeStatus box="[735,838,655,681]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Praz &amp; Al-Shahat &amp; Gadallah" authorityYear="2021" box="[874,1034,655,680]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugipuncta">
<emphasis box="[874,1034,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">M. rugipuncta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[1314,1389,655,681]" name="Jordan" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Jordan</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[151,255,691,717]" name="Morocco" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Morocco</collectingCountry>
, have the integument mostly brown with the exception of the legs, the mandibles and the antennae. 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:B7120B05FFB7FFEB5ECD32D9331EFCC1:3A64ECC8FFB0FFEB5B0030FD354DFD35" box="[1370,1393,691,717]" country="Jordan" municipality="For" name="In" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">In</location>
addition, the 
<specimenCount box="[274,412,727,753]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" type="female">two females</specimenCount>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[483,584,727,753]" name="Morocco" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Morocco</collectingCountry>
have the mesonotum more densely and finely punctate than the specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[213,288,763,789]" name="Jordan" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Jordan</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[344,410,763,789]" name="Israel" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Israel</collectingCountry>
. 
<collectingMunicipality box="[421,460,763,789]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">For</collectingMunicipality>
now, we treat all these specimens as one widely distributed species, but future studies should further examine geographic variation in this taxon
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
